Return of the Virtues
\b0 \
Virtue talk is astonishingly enduring. It is almost old as human history yet as cutting edge as any philosophical fad. \
Virtue talk lost purchase during the heady days of the Enlightenment and post-Enlightenment, especially in western Europe and North America. Yet \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
in the last 60 years in analytic philosophy, virtue ethics has achieved a kind of ascendancy. According to the Chalmers survey, 18% (almost a fifth) of analytic philosophers are virtue ethicists, with only 25% and 23% avowing deontology or consequentialism respectively. (The rest were \'93other.\'94)\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
Even so, the contemporary virtue ethicist who thinks virtue talk is indispensable has challengers on every front. \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Within virtue ethical conversations, what exact doctrines "virtue ethics" is supposed to entail is far from clear. \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 Then there are normative ethical challenges from deontologists, utilitarians, relativists, and moral skeptics. Most broadly, \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
the foundations of virtue ethics are still largely unexplored. \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 There are metaethical challenges from anti-realists, constructivists, non-cognitivists.\
